      <hedline>
        <hl1>Path to Peace, Through Jerusalem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Partem letter, commenting on July 21 editorial, says that if Pres Clinton had kept his pledge to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's united capital, the city would not now be subject to bargaining by Israelis and Palestinians</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Overtime at Camp David'' (editorial, July 21), you note that at the Middle East peace talks, the ''sharpest divisions appear to be over Jerusalem.''</p>
        <p>Time and again the United States Congress has expressed the will of the American people that Jerusalem should be recognized as the united capital of Israel. President Clinton has ignored both Congress and his own campaign promises.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Overtime at Camp David'' (editorial, July 21), you note that at the Middle East peace talks, the ''sharpest divisions appear to be over Jerusalem.''</p>
        <p>Time and again the United States Congress has expressed the will of the American people that Jerusalem should be recognized as the united capital of Israel. President Clinton has ignored both Congress and his own campaign promises.</p>
        <p>Jerusalem was not born great; it has been made a free and great capital by the toil, devotion and sacrifice of the Jewish people. If the Clinton administration had truly stood by Israel, Jerusalem would not be a bargaining chip. Jerusalem would not now be put on the table as a turkey to be carved. That it should be so today is not only to the detriment of this free metropolis, but it is also a betrayal of fundamental American values.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL PARTEM  Jerusalem, July 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
